Rodgers, however, insisted he had nothing to apologise for and hit back, saying Lineker lacked the know-how to appreciate why he made the decisions.

Rodgers said: ‘Gary is a figure I respect and he was a top player but he has never been a manager, so probably doesn’t truly understand what you are up against in terms of planning forward that way.

‘We were certainly far from throwing it away. You know, Cristiano Ronaldo has scored in every game since the Spanish Super Cup final. That shows you how hard we defended and how hard we worked. Right to the very end I think my players put in a performance that showed their passion, their commitment and their quality. That would be my answer. I am not bothered about the criticism.’ 

